<div class="page">

  <!-- HERO -->
  <div class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <div>
        <div class="hero-rule"></div>
        <div class="hero-eyebrow">A clinician&apos;s story through the operating model</div>
        <h1 class="hero-title">The bloods that<br><em>never needed</em><br>a clinic.</h1>
        <p class="hero-strap">Hannah is a GP partner. She runs the routine Iron deficiency anaemia review cycle for her practice. Layla is on her list. So are a hundred others. Every quarter she runs the same six-month FBC clinic, and every quarter the same patients miss the appointment, get rebooked, and miss again. The cycle has nothing to do with the bloods themselves. <strong>This is the story of how the model lets her hold the cohort without holding their diaries.</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-portrait-box">
        <div class="hero-portrait-circ">
          <img src="Assets/Personas/hannah.png" alt="Hannah">
        </div>
        <div class="hero-portrait-name">Hannah</div>
        <div class="hero-portrait-role">GP partner<br>Primary-care monitoring</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- RIBBON -->
  <div class="ribbon-wrap">
    <div class="ribbon-eyebrow">Hannah&apos;s journey at a glance &middot; six stages, one practice</div>
    <div class="ribbon">
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-1">
        <div class="ribbon-num">1</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">The list</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">The patients she keeps rebooking</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-2">
        <div class="ribbon-num">2</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">The missed appointment</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">15m a year, £216m, every practice in England</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-3">
        <div class="ribbon-num">3</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">The model&apos;s offer</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">Kit out, result back to her record</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-4">
        <div class="ribbon-num">4</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">First home prescriptions</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">Layla and the early cohort</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-5">
        <div class="ribbon-num">5</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">Routine monitoring in flight</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">FBCs in the record, not in the diary</div>
      </a>
      <a class="ribbon-stage" href="#stage-6">
        <div class="ribbon-num">6</div>
        <div class="ribbon-label">The practice shape now</div>
        <div class="ribbon-substage">Slots for the patients who need clinic</div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- FRAMING -->
  <div class="framing">
    <div class="framing-grid">
      <div class="framing-tile">
        <div class="framing-tile-eyebrow">The clinical North Star</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-h">The clinical accountability does not move. The venue does.</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-body">Hannah is not interested in a model that bypasses her record or sends raw numbers to a patient. The FBC result lands in her GP system as if it had been drawn at the practice. <strong>The kit changes where the blood is taken. It does not change who reads the trend or who decides what happens next.</strong></div>
      </div>
      <div class="framing-tile">
        <div class="framing-tile-eyebrow">Why this works for her practice</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-h">Phlebotomy load lifted. DNA cycle broken. Capacity returned to the patients who need clinic.</div>
        <div class="framing-tile-body"><strong>Practice-nurse phlebotomy</strong> is a scarce resource, and the routine monitoring cycle consumes a lot of it. <strong>DNA-driven rework</strong> compounds the problem: missed appointment, rebook, miss again. <strong>The home-test cycle</strong> removes the venue constraint, returns the practice nurse slot to acute or complex patients, and surfaces the trend on Hannah&apos;s screen on time.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- STAGES -->
  <div class="stages">

    <!-- STAGE 1 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-1">
      <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">01</div></div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">The list &middot; the patients she keeps rebooking</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">Hannah&apos;s list shows a hundred-odd patients on the Iron deficiency anaemia review cycle. Several names have a familiar rhythm: booked, missed, rebooked, missed again. Layla is one of them. The clinical risk lives with the patients who fall out of the cycle, not the patients she sees. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="hannah-s1"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Hannah Story/hannah-stage1.png" alt="Hannah Stage 1" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">The bloods are not the problem. The clinic was always the wrong venue for routine monitoring. The patients I lose are the patients who were never going to be able to come in at 11am on a Tuesday.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Hannah</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What the model is doing underneath</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">A practice list of patients on iron supplementation due 6-month FBC monitoring. A diary that books them in 10-minute slots. A practice-nurse rota that runs full. A familiar cluster of DNA-flagged names. <strong>The clinical question is: how do I hold these patients in the monitoring cycle without my clinic capacity being the bottleneck?</strong></div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Book, miss, rebook, miss again. Or worse, drift out of monitoring entirely and re-present with deficiency anaemia symptoms months later. The cycle treats every patient as if they can come in on a Tuesday morning. Most can. Some can&apos;t. The ones who can&apos;t are the ones the cycle quietly drops.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">What the care team sees</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">Her practice nurse. Her practice manager on diary capacity. Anita on the ICB / GP commissioner side. The patient.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
          <div class="crosslinks-row">
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Who</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Hannah.html" target="_blank">Hannah persona</a>
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">H&amp;M</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Layla Journey.html" target="_blank">Layla&apos;s journey</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- STAGE 2 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-2">
      <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">02</div></div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">The missed appointment &middot; the structural problem</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">Fifteen million general-practice appointments are missed in England every year. Two hundred and sixteen million pounds. The routine monitoring slot is precisely the kind of appointment that breaks first. The patient gets blamed for &lsquo;not engaging&rsquo;; the venue takes none of the responsibility. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="hannah-s2"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Hannah Story/hannah-stage2.png" alt="Hannah Stage 2" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">Layla wasn&apos;t refusing care. She was keeping her job, getting her kids to school, looking after a parent. The clinic was always the wrong venue. The risk was always in the model, not in her.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Hannah</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What the model is doing underneath</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">Around 15 million general-practice appointments are missed each year, costing the NHS ~£216m. Routine monitoring appointments DNA at a higher rate than acute or complex visits. Around 307 million GP sessions are scheduled annually. <strong>The home-test cycle is the way to remove the venue cost from the bloods that never needed clinic in the first place.</strong></div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">Patients drop out of monitoring. Deficiency anaemia gets re-detected later, often via A&amp;E or an acute appointment. The cost lands on a different part of the system. The original missed appointment looks &lsquo;just&rsquo; like £30. The downstream cost is much larger.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">What the care team sees</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">Anita, on the ICB / GP commissioner side, paying for the access problem. The other GP partners running the same DNA curve. The practice nurses doing the rebooking work.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="crosslinks">
          <div class="crosslinks-label">Where this lives in the model</div>
          <div class="crosslinks-row">
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">Who</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Persona Anita.html" target="_blank">Anita &middot; ICB / GP commissioner</a>
            <span class="crosslinks-tag">H&amp;M</span>
            <a href="HomeTest Operating Model - Layla Journey.html" target="_blank">Layla&apos;s journey</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- STAGE 3 -->
    <div class="stage" id="stage-3">
      <div class="stage-side"><div class="stage-number">03</div></div>
      <div class="stage-main">
        <div class="stage-eyebrow">The model&apos;s offer &middot; kit out, result to her record</div>
        <h2 class="stage-title">A home FBC kit ordered against Hannah&apos;s prescription. The sample comes back to the lab. The result lands in her GP system before the appointment that did not happen would have happened. The clinical role is preserved. The diary is not. <span class="hm-witness" data-moment="hannah-s3"></span></h2>

        <div class="stage-image" style="padding:0;border:none;background:none;margin-bottom:22px;"><img src="Assets/Hannah Story/hannah-stage3.png" alt="Hannah Stage 3" style="width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:12px;display:block;box-shadow:0 8px 24px rgba(0,32,64,0.12);"></div>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p class="pull-quote-text">If the result lands in the record, with the trend, and the clinical interpretation is still mine, the kit is just a change of venue. The clinical accountability does not move. That is what I needed to know.</p>
          <div class="pull-quote-attribution">Hannah</div>
        </div>

        <div class="whats-happening">
          <div class="whats-happening-label">What the model is doing underneath</div>
          <div class="whats-happening-body">The result returns to Hannah&apos;s GP system via the framework&apos;s EPR write-back. The trend display is unchanged. The clinical review remains hers. Threshold alerts escalate to her in the same way an in-clinic FBC would. <strong>The patient experiences a kit. Hannah experiences the result on the same screen as always.</strong></div>
        </div>

        <div class="old-way">
          <div class="old-way-label">The old way</div>
          <div class="old-way-body">A model that sends FBC results directly to the patient as raw numbers, or sits the results in a parallel system her practice does not see. Either would have killed adoption. Hannah is not interested in a model that routes around her.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="careteam">
          <div class="careteam-icon">&#x1F465;</div>
          <div class="careteam-body">
            <div class="careteam-label">What the care team sees</div>
            <div class="careteam-text">Aisha, the Clinical Safety Group lead, owning the safety case for primary-care home testing. Ngozi, the Information Governance lead, on the EPR write-back DSA. The kit supplier on lab assurance.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

